{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"693ce4aa-bd7d-4cd2-b8ca-123993ca3bf4","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. These contain the stack trace, exception type, and thread info.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same reports.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   macOS disables core dumps by default, and SIP may block them even when enabled.\n\n**For NativeAOT specifically**, Apple's `.ips` crash reports are usually your best bet since `createdump` isn't bundled. The report includes the faulting address and native stack frames, which you can symbolicate with `lldb` if you have debug symbols.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a3d1db8-d805-4b42-9338-aa8e270a2658","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":309,"requestId":"980D:3387D:540C360:5C9AA36:69F40648"},"id":"c34f2767-b1cb-4898-8029-08215072b75d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:48:02.381Z","parentId":"065ceddd-7e25-4dd6-a5e8-d3c231d2d506"}
